Custom functions

# function for getting lnRR for proportional data

lnrrp <- function(m1, m2, n1, n2) {
    # arcsine transforamtion
    asin_trans <- function(p) {
        asin(sqrt(p))
    }
    # SD for arcsine distribution (see Wiki -
    # https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arcsine_distribution)
    var1 <- 1/8
    var2 <- 1/8
    # lnRR - with 2nd order correction
    lnrr <- log(asin_trans(m1)/asin_trans(m2)) + 0.5 * ((var1/(n1 * asin_trans(m1)^2)) - 
        (var2/(n2 * asin_trans(m2)^2)))
    
    var <- var1/(n1 * asin_trans(m1)^2) + var1^2/(2 * n1^2 * asin_trans(m1)^4) + 
        var2/(n2 * asin_trans(m2)^2) + var2^2/(2 * n2^2 * asin_trans(m2)^4)
    
    invisible(data.frame(yi = lnrr, vi = var))
}

# function for getting lnRR for mean data

lnrrm <- function(m1, m2, n1, n2, sd1, sd2) {
    # lnRR - with 2nd order correction
    lnrr <- log(m1/m2) + 0.5 * (((sd1^2)/(n1 * m1^2)) - ((sd2^2)/(n2 * m2^2)))
    
    var <- sd1^2/(n1 * m1^2) + sd1^4/(2 * n1^2 * m2^4) + sd2^2/(n2 * m2^2) + sd2^4/(2 * 
        n2^2 * m2^4)
    
    invisible(data.frame(yi = lnrr, vi = var))
}

# deleting unusable rows ##### excluding Vasectomy TODO this is important!!!!!
dat <- dat_full1 %>% filter(is.na(Treatment_lifespan_variable) == FALSE) %>% filter(Type_of_sterilization != 
    "Vasectomy") %>% mutate_if(is.character, as.factor)
# dim(dat) #116 (i.e. removed 2 rows)

# separating two kinds of effect size (longevity vs. mortality measures)
effect_type <- ifelse(str_detect(dat$Lifespan_parameter, "Me"), "longevity", "mortality")
# table(effect_type)

# add new variables
dat$Effect_ID <- 1:nrow(dat)  # effect-level ID
dat$Phylogeny <- sub(" ", "_", dat$Species_Latin)  #Pjylogeny species names (for the tree) based on Latin names
dat$Effect_type <- as.factor(effect_type)

# extract publication year from Study variable
dat$Year <- as.numeric(gsub(".*?([0-9]+).*", "\\1", dat$Study))  #equivalent to parse_number(dat$Study)but does not create problems for NA

Summarise the dataset

Note that ES have not been calculated yet (use prelim.R code to do so).

Look at the overall pattern of missing data.

General summary

  • Number of effect sizes: 116
  • Number of studies: 50
  • Publication years: from 1930 to 2021
  • Simple list of studies as short references: Arriola Apelo et al 2020, Asdell and Joshi 1976, Asdell et al 1967, Benedusi et al 2015, Bronson 1981, Bronson 1982, Cargil et al 2003, Cheng 2019, Cox and Calsbeek 2010, Cox et al 2010, Cox et al 2014, Dorner 1973, Drori and Folman 1976, Garratt et al 2021, Gipps and Jewel 1979, Hamilton 1965, Hamilton and Mestler 1969, Hamilton et al 1969, Hoffman et al 2018, Holland et al 1997, Huang et al 2017, Iwasa et al 2018, Jacob et al 2004 A, Jacob et al 2004 B, Jewel 1997, Kirkman and Yau, Kirkpatrick and Turner 2004, Mason et al 2009, Min et al 2012, Mitchel et al 1999, Moore et al 2001, Muhlock 1959, Nieschlag et al 1993, Oneil et al 2013, Oneil et al 2015, Parker et al 2013, Ramsey 2005, Ramsey et al 2021, Reedy et al 2016, Sichuk 1965, Slonaker 1930, Storer et al 1982, Talbert and Hamilton 1965, Tapprest et al 2017, Twigg et al 2000, Urfer et al 2019, Waters et al 2011, Williams et al 2007, Wilson et al 2019, Zakeri et al 2019
  • Number of species: 14
  • Simple list of species Latin names (also stored in “Phylogeny” variable): Mus musculus, Rattus norvegicus, Felis catus, Canis lupus, Anolis sagrei, Myodes glareolus, Homo sapiens, Rattus argentiventer, Ovis aries, Mesocricetus auratus, Equus ferus, Trichosurus vulpecula, Phascolarctos cinereus, Oryctolagus cuniculus
  • Number of data points for females: 68, and data points form males: 48
